CO-TENANCY AND SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT THIS CO-TENANCY SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT (???Agreement???) is entered into on January 20, 2023 (the ???Effective Date???), by and among (i) Gravel Pit Solar, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (???Co-Owner 1???), Gravel Pit Solar III, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (???Co-Owner 2???) and Gravel Pit Solar IV, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (???Co-Owner 3???; each of Co-Owner 3, Co-Owner 2 and Co-Owner 1 is sometimes referred to herein individually as a ???Co- Owner??? and collectively as ???Co-Owners???) and (ii) DESRI Gravel Pit Construction Borrower, L.L.C., a Delaware limited liability company, in its capacity as the manager of the Shared Facilities (the ???Manager???). The Co-Owners and Manger are sometimes referred to collectively as the ???Parties??? and each, separately as a ???Party???. RECITALS WHEREAS, the Co-Owners and their Affiliates are developing and have developed a solar powered alternative energy electric generating facility located on real property in Town of East Windsor, Hartford County, Connecticut (the ???Facility???), in two phases, each such phase with a nameplate capacity of approximately: Co-Owner 2 Facility Phase: 50 MWAC Co-Owner 3 Facility Phase: 70 MWAC WHEREAS, certain of the Co-Owners have entered into, or will enter into, the Shared Facilities Agreement dated on or about the date hereof by and among Co-Owner 2, Co-Owner 3 and Manager in relation to apportioning undivided rights in certain material project documents and undivided rights to use real and personal property acquired or to be acquired for their portion of the Facility. WHEREAS, the Co-Owner 1 has entered into the Interconnection Agreement, of which the Co- Owners wish to have a right to an undivided interest in the Delivery Capability thereunder (the ???Undivided Delivery Capability???). WHEREAS, the Manager plans to procure, install and construct, or has procured, installed and constructed, certain facilities for electrical transmission, point of interconnection, communications?? structures and other facilities, including the Shared Substation Equipment, which are further described in Exhibit B (the ???Shared Facilities??? and together with the Undivided Delivery Capability and the Interconnection Agreement, the ???Shared Assets???) and the Co-Owners wish to own an undivided right to use such Shared Facilities. NOW THEREFORE, in consideration of the recitals, the premises, covenants and conditions contained herein, and other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which the Parties acknowledge, the Parties agree as follows: ARTICLE I - DEFINITIONS, INTERPRETATIONS AND EXHIBITS 1.1 Definitions. As used in this Agreement, including the Recitals, and except as required by grammatical usage and apart from proper nouns, each capitalized term has the meaning given to it in this Agreement and in the Schedule of Definitions attached as Exhibit A.
1.2 Interpretation. In this Agreement, unless a clear, contrary intention appears: (a) the singular includes the plural and vice versa; (b) reference to any Person includes such Person???s successors and assigns but, in the case of a Party, only if such assigns are permitted by this Agreement, and reference to a Person in a particular capacity excludes such Person in any other capacity; (c) reference to any gender includes each other gender; (d) reference to any agreement (including this Agreement), document or instrument means such agreement, document or instrument as amended or modified and in effect from time to time in accordance with the terms thereof and, if applicable, the terms of this Agreement; (e) reference to any Law means such Law as amended, modified, codified, or reenacted, in whole or in part, and in effect from time to time, including, if applicable, rules and regulations promulgated thereunder; (f) reference to any Section means such Section of this Agreement, and references in any Section or definition to any clause means such clause of such Section or definition; (g) ???hereunder,??? ???hereof,??? ???hereto??? and words of similar import shall be deemed references to this Agreement as a whole and not to any particular Section or other provision of this Agreement; (h) ???including??? means including without limiting the generality of any description such term; and (i) relative to the determination of any period of time, ???from??? means ???from and including???, ???to??? means ???to be excluding??? and ???through??? means ???through and including???. 1.3 Incorporation of Recitals and Exhibits. The Recitals set forth in this Agreement and the Exhibits attached hereto are incorporated into this Agreement by reference for all purposes. ARTICLE II - TERM OF AGREEMENT 2.1 Term. This Agreement shall become effective as of the Effective Date and shall remain in force and effect until the date that the Facility is decommissioned, unless earlier terminated by the Parties. 2.2 Survival. Any obligations of a Party to any other Party, including payment obligations and indemnity obligations, as a result of this Agreement which accrued prior to or as a result of termination of this Agreement shall survive termination of this Agreement. ARTICLE III - OWNERSHIP OF SHARED ASSETS 3.1 Ownership Interests. 3.1.1 As of the Effective Date, (i) Manager hereby grants, and each Co-Owner shall own, an undivided right to use, as a tenant-in-common, the Shared Facilities, and (ii) Co-Owner 1 hereby grants, and each Co-Owner shall own, an undivided interest, as a tenant-in-common, in the Interconnection Agreement and Undivided Delivery Capability, each grant based upon each Co-Owner???s percentage interest as set forth in Exhibit B, as updated from time to time in accordance with Section 3.1.2 below (such interest of each Co-Owner being referred to in this Agreement as its ???Ownership Interest???). 3.1.2 In the event that a Co-Owner???s nameplate capacity (as set forth in the Recitals to this Agreement) increases or decreases following the Effective Date, such Co-Owner shall promptly provide written notice to Manager detailing out such capacity change. Any change in a Co-Owner???s nameplate capacity shall have a correlating change to such Co-Owner???s Ownership Interest for the purposes of this Agreement
3.2 Shared Facilities; Undivided Delivery Capability. 3.2.1 The Manager plans to procure, install and construct, or has procured, installed and constructed, the Shared Facilities, which may be altered or reconstructed by amendment in accordance with this Agreement. 3.2.2 Co-Owner 1 has entered into the Interconnection Agreement, of which the Co- Owners wish to have a right to the Undivided Delivery Capability, which may be altered or reconstructed by amendment in accordance with this Agreement. 3.2.3 Each Co-Owner of the Shared Assets shall be entitled to use such Shared Assets in accordance with its Undivided Use Interest. In the event that the Delivery Capability of the Shared Assets exceeds the capability provided in the Interconnection Agreement, with Transmission Owner???s and Transmission Provider???s written consent and approval, each Co- Owner???s Undivided Use Interest will be increased pro rata in accordance with its Ownership Interest for so long as the Delivery Capability is in excess of the capability provided in the Interconnection Agreement. For the avoidance of doubt, the Co-Owners will not exceed the maximum permissible output of the Facility pursuant to the Interconnection Agreement, unless all necessary approvals and consents are obtained (including from Transmission Owner and Transmission Provider). If the Interconnection Agreement is terminated, such Co-Owner???s undivided interest in the Delivery Capability shall be suspended until the Interconnection Agreement is reinstated or Manager enters into a new interconnection agreement for the Facility. 3.3 Reserved. 3.4 Exclusions. Notwithstanding the foregoing, if any portion of the Shared Assets, Ownership Interest, permits, real estate rights, or similar rights that by their terms or by operation of law or any Applicable Law would become void, voidable, terminable or revocable or in respect of which a Co-Owner or Manager would be deemed to be in breach or default thereunder if included in the Shared Assets hereunder, such portion of the Ownership Interests, Shared Assets, permits, real estate rights, or similar right, as applicable, is expressly excepted and excluded from the Shared Assets hereunder and terms of this Agreement to the extent necessary to avoid such voidness, voidability, terminability, revocability, breach or default. 3.5 Additional Co-Owners. Each Co-Owner hereby agrees and acknowledges that additional Co-Owners and, as a result, additional Facilities, may become Co-Owners of the Shared Assets. The Co- Owners shall reasonably cooperate in order to amend this Agreement and take such other reasonable actions in order to incorporate such additional Co-Owners into this Agreement. ARTICLE IV ??? METERING, MEASUREMENT OF ENERGY DELIVERIES AND LOSSES 4.1 Measurement of Energy. Energy transmitted by the Co-Owners to the Shared Facilities shall be measured and allocated between the Co-Owners of the Shared Facilities as set forth on Attachment B-1 to Exhibit B. 4.2 Testing and Repair of Co-Owner???s Meters.
4.2.1 Inspection and Testing. If applicable and in conformance with the applicable Interconnection Agreement(s), a Co-Owner will cause meters (other than revenue meters owned by the interconnection provider and check meters owned by the individual Co-Owner) to be inspected and tested upon its installation and at least once every twenty-four (24) months thereafter and at any other reasonable time upon the other Co-Owner???s request, which may not be made more than three times in said twenty-four (24) month period. The Co-Owner requesting such inspection and testing will pay the costs of same, unless the results of the test show the Co- Owner???s meter to be inaccurate by more than half of one percent (0.5%), in which case the Co- Owners will share the costs of the test. Each Co-Owner will give the other Co-Owners reasonable advance notice of tests of its meter and the other Co-Owners have the right to witness such tests. 4.2.2 Calibration or Repair. If a test shows a Co-Owner???s meter to be inaccurate, the owner of the meter will use reasonable efforts to cause its meter to be calibrated, repaired or replaced. 4.3 Allocation of Losses. Any interruption, reduction in deliveries of, or other curtailment of electrical power through the Shared Facilities, or to the point of interconnection designated in the Interconnection Agreement, in each case instructed by the Transmission Provider or such other person entitled to direct such interruption, reduction or curtailment pursuant to the Interconnection Agreement or applicable law (the ???Directing Entity???), shall be allocated to one or more Co-Owners as the Directing Entity shall determine and apportion to such Co-Owners. If and only to the extent that the Directing Entity does not determine and apportion such interruption, reduction in deliveries or other curtailment of electrical power, the Manager shall, to the fullest extent possible allocate such interruption, reduction in deliveries or other curtailment of electrical power to the Co-Owner whose actions or inactions caused such interruption, reduction, or curtailment; provided, if and to the extent such interruption, reduction in deliveries or other curtailment of electrical power cannot be attributed to the actions or inactions of any Co-Owner, the Manager shall allocate such interruption, reduction in deliveries or other curtailment of electrical power to each Co-Owner in proportion to its respective Ownership Interest. To the extent that during such interruption, reduction in deliveries or other curtailment of electrical power, any Co-Owner is not using any portion or all of the capacity allocated to it under this Section, the Co-Owners agree to reasonably cooperate to allow the other Co-Owner to temporarily use such capacity not being used during such period of non-use. The foregoing provisions, however, do not apply to interruptions, reductions in deliveries or other curtailments attributed to (i) compliance with any applicable power purchase agreement or (ii) dispatch down instructions received by a Co-Owner, or the Manager as the case may be, from the Transmission Owner or another Directing Entity and directed at a particular Co-Owner. Actions taken by the Manager under this Section shall be taken in a fair and neutral manner that does not disproportionately benefit or burden one Co-Owner over another. ARTICLE V - RELATIONSHIP OF MANAGER AND CO-OWNERS 5.1 Actions Taken by Manager. Unless as otherwise agreed in writing between the Parties, all actions or activities a Co-Owner has the right or obligation to take or perform on or with respect to the Shared Assets shall be taken or performed by Manager. A Co-Owner and its invitees shall have the right to inspect the Shared Assets, provided however, that such inspection occur during normal business hours and not unreasonably interfere with the day to business operations of the Manager.
5.2 Consent or Approval. Manager shall not grant any consent or approval of the Co-Owners required pursuant to any agreement requiring such consent, without the prior written consent of the Co- Owner, which shall not be unreasonably withheld or delayed. ARTICLE VI - COVENANTS 6.1 Covenants. Each Party hereby covenants as follows: 6.1.1 except as otherwise set forth in this Agreement, such Party???s use of the Shared Assets shall not in any way materially interfere with the use and enjoyment by the other Parties of their respective interests in the Shared Assets or other rights arising under this Agreement; 6.1.2 such Party shall perform its obligations under this Agreement in accordance with (a) all Applicable Laws, (b) Good Utility Practice, and (c) the terms and conditions of the Material Project Documents to which it is a party (if any); and 6.1.3 such Party shall not act or fail to act in a manner that would interfere with any other Party???s ownership or use of the Shared Assets, including but not limited to any such interference that would curtail or diminish another Party???s ability to deliver the electrical output of its portion of the Facility.
ARTICLE VII ??? DAMAGE OR DESTRUCTION OF SHARED FACILITIES 7.1 Damage or Destruction. In the event of any damage or destruction to or other failure of all or any part of the Shared Facilities that affects the business operations of one or more Co-Owners (each an ???Affected Party???), such Affected Party shall, subject to any contrary requirements set forth in the Material Project Documents, and any other power purchase agreement or offtake agreement to which a Co-Owner is a party, or by Applicable Law, take all commercially reasonable actions as may be necessary or appropriate to repair or replace the affected Shared Facilities in order to restore the affected Shared Facilities to substantially the same condition (or better) as before such damage or destruction and, subject to Section 10.2 below, any costs associated with such actions, after accounting for recoveries under any applicable insurance policies, will be shared by the Co-Owners pro rata based on their Ownership Interests, as applicable. Following any such damage, destruction or failure, if (i) the Affected Party fails to diligently proceed with the repair or replacement of the affected Shared Facilities in accordance with the preceding sentence or (ii) the Affected Party notifies the other affected Co-Owners that it does not intend to repair or replace the affected Shared Facilities, then in either such case, the other affected Co-Owners shall have the right to repair or replace the affected Shared Facilities (or a portion thereof sufficient to serve such other Co-Owners??? requirements) and continue the operation and maintenance thereof for the remainder of the Term; provided, that in such event and subject to Section 10.2 below, the Affected Party shall be obligated to the Co-Owners funding the repair or replacement of the Shared Facilities for the costs of repair or replacement on a pro rata basis based on its Ownership Interest; and provided further, that such other Co-Owners shall not unreasonably interfere with the business operations of the Affected Party. In all events, the Co-Owners shall cooperate with each other in good faith to minimize the impact thereof on the Co-Owners and their respective business operations.
ARTICLE VIII - EVENTS OF DEFAULT; REMEDIES 8.1 Defaults. The occurrence and continuation of any of the following events shall constitute an event of default of a Party under this Agreement (an ???Event of Default???): 8.1.1 Bankruptcy. If a Party files a petition or otherwise commences, or authorizes or acquiesces in the commencement of, a proceeding or cause under any bankruptcy, insolvency, receivership or similar law for the protection of creditors or suffers the filing of an involuntary bankruptcy petition or proceeding commenced against it, which in the case of an involuntary petition or proceeding remains undismissed and unstayed for ninety (90) days; 8.1.2 Other Defaults. A Party fails to cure (a) any breach of the covenant set forth in Section 6.1 by the earlier to occur of (i) fifteen (15) days following written notice from any other Party specifying the nature of such breach, or (ii) the date by which such breach is required to be cured to avoid an event of default under the applicable agreement covered by clause (c) of such Section, or (b) any other unexcused and uncured failure to perform, in any material respect, any obligation under this Agreement, which could reasonably be expected to materially and adversely affect another Party???s realization of the material benefits of this Agreement or the ability of a Party to perform its material obligations under this Agreement, within thirty (30) days following written notice from any other Party specifying the nature of the failure to perform, provided that with respect to clause (b), if the default is not reasonably capable of being cured within thirty (30) days, then the defaulting Party may be allowed such longer period as the Parties mutually agree upon and as may be reasonably necessary under the circumstances to cure such failure so long as the defaulting Party is pursuing a cure with reasonable diligence; 8.1.3 Default by Manager. Manager fails to perform any of its material obligations hereunder in accordance with this Agreement, with respect to all or a portion of the Shared Assets, and such failure is not cured within ten (10) days following written notice by a Co-Owner; provided that, that if such failure by Manager materially interferes with a Co-Owner???s undivided interest in Shared Assets in which it has an Ownership Interest, or operation of its Facility, only such advance written notice, if any, as may be reasonably practicable under the circumstances shall be required, but if such advance notice is not provided, written notice thereof shall be provided promptly thereafter by a Co-Owner to Manager and such failure is not cured within the period specified in such notice; 8.1.4 Seizure of Property. Any substantial property of the Manager or a Co-Owner is subjected to any levy, seizure, assignment or sale for or by any creditor or Governmental Authority that materially affects that Manager???s or such Co-Owner???s ability to perform under this Agreement; or 8.1.5 Merger, Consolidation without Assumption of Obligations. The Co-Owner consolidates or amalgamates with, or merges with or into, or transfers all or substantially all of its assets to, another entity and, at the time of such consolidation, amalgamation, merger or transfer, the resulting, surviving or transferee entity fails to assume all the obligations of such Co- Owner under this Agreement to which it or its predecessor was a party by operation of law or pursuant to an agreement reasonably satisfactory to the other Co-Owners.
8.2 Remedies upon Default. 8.2.1 If any default is not cured within the applicable cure period (if any) provided in Section 8.1 by making or tendering the required payment or performance, each non-defaulting Party shall have the right (i) to cure the default at the expense of the defaulting Party, in which event the defaulting Party shall reimburse the curing Party or Parties all of the curing Party???s or Parties??? costs of cure within thirty (30) days of invoice, or curing Party or Parties may offset such costs against any sums then or thereafter owed by the curing Party or Parties to the defaulting Party; (ii) to enforce specific performance; or (iii) to enforce any other remedy available to the non-defaulting Parties at law or in equity, subject to Section 8.2.3 and Article XI. 8.2.2 Notwithstanding anything contained in this Agreement to the contrary, if a Co- Owner???s default under this Agreement, creates a material interference with another Co-Owner???s (a ???Non-Defaulting Co-Owner???) operations or maintenance of such Non-Defaulting Co-Owner???s portion of the Facility, the Non-Defaulting Co-Owner(s) shall have the right to any expedited remedies that may be available hereunder at law or in equity, including the right to cure such default as provided in Section 8.2.1, and the right to reimbursement of all reasonable costs actually incurred by such Non-Defaulting Co-Owner in effecting such cure. 8.2.3 In no event shall any Party be entitled to terminate this Agreement on account of default by another Party hereto. None of the bankruptcy or insolvency of a Party, or default by a Party under this Agreement shall be grounds for terminating this Agreement. ARTICLE IX - LENDER PROTECTION 9.1 Right to Encumber and Assign. Pursuant and subject to Section 12.3, each Party may, upon written notice to the other Parties (but without the other Parties??? consent or approval), mortgage, collaterally assign, or otherwise encumber and grant a security interest in this Agreement, the Shared Facilities or the electrical and/or transmission capacity of the Shared Assets (collectively, the ???Security Assets???), which said mortgage, collateral assignment, encumbrance or security interests in all or a part of the Shared Assets are collectively referred to herein as ???Lender???s Liens??? and the holders of the Lender???s Liens, their designees, agents, trustees, nominees and assigns are referred to herein as ???Lenders???. Subject to Section 12.3, each Party shall also have the right, upon written notice but without the other Parties??? consent or approval, to sell, convey, lease or assign all of its assets to a Permitted Assignee. Each Party agrees to execute any documents which may reasonably be required by another Party, a Lender or a Permitted Assignee, including but not limited to any document in connection with a governmental permit, approval, authorization, entitlement or other consent. Under no circumstances shall any Lender or Permitted Assignee have any greater rights of ownership or use or management of the Shared Assets than the respective rights granted to the Parties in this Agreement. 9.2 Obligations. As a precondition to exercising any remedies related to any alleged default by a Party under this Agreement, a Party shall give written notice of default to each other Party and each Lender and Permitted Assignee that has been previously identified to such other Party at the same time it delivers notice of default to the defaulting Party, specifying in detail the alleged event of default and the required cure. Each such Lender and Permitted Assignee, collectively, shall have the same amount of time to cure the default as to the defaulting Party???s interest in the Shared Assets as is given to the defaulting Party and the same right to cure any default as the defaulting Party. The cure period for such
Lenders and Permitted Assignees shall begin to run at the end of the cure period given to Co-Owners or Manager, as applicable, in this Agreement. In the event that no cure period is expressly set forth in this Agreement, the cure period for any Lender or Permitted Assignee shall be thirty (30) days. The Lenders of the defaulting Party shall have the absolute right (but not the obligation), to substitute themselves for the defaulting Party and perform the duties of the defaulting Party hereunder for purposes of curing such event of default. Each Party expressly consents to such substitution, agrees to accept such performance and authorizes such Lenders (or their respective employees, agents, representatives or contractors) to enter upon the Shared Facilities to complete such performance with all of the rights and privileges of the defaulting Party hereunder. 9.3 Lender Obligations. Any Lender that does not directly hold an interest under this Agreement, or whose interest is held solely for security purposes, shall have no obligation or liability to any other Party for performance of a Party???s obligations under this Agreement prior to the time the Lender directly holds an interest in this Agreement, or succeeds to absolute title to a Party???s interest. A Lender shall be liable to perform obligations of a Party to the other Parties under this Agreement only for and during the period it directly holds such interest (other than where such interest is in the nature of a security interest only). Any assignment permitted under this Agreement shall release a Party or other assignor from obligations accruing after the date that liability is assumed by a transferee, but the assigning Party shall continue to be liable to the other Parties for all performance due by the assigning Party for matters that have accrued and are unsatisfied as of the date of the assignment. Further, in the event that a Lender elects to (i) perform a Party???s obligations under this Agreement, (ii) continue operation of the Shared Assets, (iii) acquire any portion of a Party???s right, title or interest in all or any of the Shared Assets, or (iv) enter into a new joint ownership agreement as provided in Section 9.6, then such Lender shall not have any personal liability to a Party in connection therewith, and a non-defaulting Party???s sole recourse in the event of default by such Lender shall be to execute against such Lender???s interest in the Shared Assets. Moreover, any Lender or other Party who acquires the Shared Assets pursuant to foreclosure or an assignment in lieu of foreclosure shall not be liable to perform any obligations under the Agreement to the extent the same are incurred or accrue after such Lender or other Party no longer has ownership of the Shared Assets. 9.4 Lender???s Right to Possession, Right to Acquire and Right to Assign. Subject to the terms of the applicable financing and security documents to which it is a party, a Lender shall have the absolute right: (i) to assign its Lender???s Lien; (ii) to enforce its Lender???s Lien and acquire title to all or any portion of the Shared Assets by any lawful means; (iii) to take possession of and operate all or any portion of the Shared Assets and to perform all obligations to be performed by a Party under this Agreement, or to cause a receiver to be appointed to do so; and (iv) to acquire all or any portion of the Shared Assets by foreclosure or by an assignment in lieu of foreclosure and thereafter without any Party???s consent to assign or transfer all or any portion of the Shared Assets to another Person. No Party???s consent shall be required for any of the foregoing, and upon acquisition of the interests of all or any portion of the Shared Assets by a Lender or any other Party who acquires the same from or on behalf of the Lender, each Party shall recognize the Lender or such other Party (as the case may be) as the other Party???s proper successor, and this Agreement shall remain in full force and effect. 9.5 Opportunity to Cure. Following acquisition of all or a portion of the Shared Assets by a Lender as a result of either foreclosure or acceptance of an assignment in lieu of foreclosure, or by a purchaser at a foreclosure sale, this Agreement shall continue in full force and effect and the Lender or Party acquiring title to the Shared Assets shall, as promptly as reasonably possible, commence the cure
of all defaults under this Agreement and thereafter diligently process such cure to completion; provided, however, that such Lender or Party acquiring title to the Shared Assets shall not be required to cure those defaults which are not reasonably susceptible of being cured or performed by such Party (???Non-Curable Defaults???). Non-Curable Defaults shall be deemed waived by a non-defaulting Party upon completion of foreclosure proceedings or acquisition of the defaulting Party???s interest in the Shared Assets by such replacement Party. If a Lender is prohibited by any process or injunction issued by any court or by reason of any action of any court having jurisdiction over any bankruptcy or insolvency proceeding involving the defaulting Party from commencing or prosecuting the appropriate judicial or non-judicial proceedings, then any cure period for commencing such proceedings shall be extended for the period of such prohibition. 9.6 New Agreement. In the event that this Agreement is rejected or disaffirmed pursuant to bankruptcy law or any other law affecting creditors??? rights, then, so long as a Lender has cured any such monetary event of default and is making commercially reasonable efforts to cure any such non-monetary event of default as provided herein, the non-defaulting Party shall, promptly upon written request from such Lender received within sixty (60) days after any such event, without demanding additional consideration therefor, enter into a new shared facilities agreement with such Lender, which new shared facilities agreement shall (i) contain the same covenants, agreements, terms, provisions and limitations as this Agreement (except for any requirements that have been fulfilled by the Parties prior to such termination, foreclosure, rejection or disaffirmance), and (ii) be for a term commencing on the date of such termination, foreclosure, rejection or disaffirmance and continuing for the remaining term of this Agreement before giving effect to such termination, foreclosure, rejection or disaffirmance. At the option of the Lender, the new shared facilities agreement may be executed by a designee, nominees, agent or trustee of such Lender, with the Lender assuming the burdens and obligations of the defaulting Party thereunder. If more than one Lender makes a written request for a new shared facilities agreement pursuant hereto, then the same shall be delivered to the Lender whose lien is senior in priority, as agreed in writing by such Lender or as determined by a court of competent jurisdiction. 9.7 Lender Consent. Except to the extent permitted under the terms of any financing agreement to which it is a party, notwithstanding any provision of this Agreement to the contrary, (i) a Party shall not agree to a modification or amendment of this Agreement if the same could reasonably be expected to materially prejudice the rights or remedies of a Lender or impair the security for a Lender???s Lien and (ii) a Party shall not accept a termination of this Agreement without the prior written consent of each Lender that has been previously identified in writing to such Party. 9.8 Subordination. All of the rights, titles, estates and interests granted or assigned by Manager to, or otherwise held or possessed by any one or more of the Project Subsidiaries in, to or under the Site Lease, any rights, titles, estates or interests thereunder or in, to or under the Specified Land, have been granted or assigned subject and subordinate to and are and shall be subject and subordinate to the Mortgage, and to all of the liens, assignments, security interests and terms and provisions thereof. Upon any foreclosure of the Mortgage or deed in lieu thereof upon Manager???s leasehold estate under the Site Lease or upon such estate and any rights, title, estates or interests of any Co-Owner hereunder, the foreclosing Lender may elect to terminate this Agreement.
ARTICLE X - INDEMNIFICATION AND LIMITATION OF LIABILITY 10.1 Indemnification by Co-Owners. Without any duplication of any indemnification provided by the Manager pursuant to Section 9.3 hereof, to the fullest extent permitted by law, each Co-Owner (an ???Indemnitor???) shall release, defend, indemnify and hold harmless the other Co-Owners and the Manager and their respective affiliates, members, partners, contractors, subcontractors and agents, and the directors, shareholders, officers, agents and employees of each of them, from and against all Claims which are caused by or arise out of the fault or negligent acts or omissions, whether active or passive, of the Indemnitor in connection with activities under this Agreement, or result from any breach by the Indemnitor of any provision of this Agreement or of any Exhibit hereto. Notwithstanding the forgoing, no such indemnification shall be provided to a Co-Owner or Manager by Indemnitor for the gross negligence or willful misconduct of another Co-Owner or Manager. 10.2 Indemnification Due to Facility Malfunction. Gravel Pit Solar III, LLC FERC Electric Tariff No. 1 1. Availability. Gravel Pit Solar III, LLC (???Seller???) will make available at wholesale under this Tariff: (a) electric energy and/or capacity; and (b) the following ancillary services: (i) PJM: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. ("PJM") and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection. (i) New York: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute non-synchronous, 30- minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc. (ii) New England: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10- minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc. (iii) California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation ("CAISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO. (iv) MISO: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. (???MISO???) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to MISO. (v) Southwest Power Pool: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. (???SPP???) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to SPP. (vi) Third-party Ancillary Services: Seller offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve-Supplemental, and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider???s OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization. 2. Applicability. This Tariff is applicable to all wholesale sales by Seller of electric energy, electric capacity, and ancillary services listed in Section 1 of this Tariff not otherwise subject to a tariff or rate schedule of Seller that is on file with the Commission. 3. Rates. All sales shall be made at rates established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller. 4. Other Terms and Conditions. All other terms and conditions of sales shall be established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller. 5. Revisions. This Tariff may be revised by Seller by unilaterally making the appropriate filing with the Commission pursuant to the provisions of Section 205 of the Federal Power Act. 6. Duration. This Tariff shall continue to be effective until terminated or changed. Such termination or change shall take effect in accordance with the applicable regulatory requirements. 7. Compliance with Commission Regulations. Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning Seller???s market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes Seller to engage in affiliate sales under this tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the Seller???s market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning Seller???s market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this tariff.
8. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority. In Gravel Pit Solar III, LLC, Docket No. ER24-2534-001 (2024), the Commission granted Seller the following waivers and blanket authorization: (i) waiver of the accounting, reporting, and other requirements of 18 C.F.R. Parts 41, 101 (with the exception that waiver of the provisions of Part 101 that apply to hydropower licensees is not granted with respect to licensed hydropower projects), and 141 with the exception of Section 141.15; (ii) waiver of the reporting requirements of Subparts B and C of Part 35 of the Commission???s regulations, except Sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15 and 35.16; and (iii) Blanket authorization under 18 C.F.R. Part 34 of all future issuances of securities and assumptions of liability. Seller???s tariff excludes market-based sales to customers located within the Puget Sound Energy Balancing Authority Area. See Puget Sound Energy, Inc., 181 FERC ?? 61,008 (2022). 9. Mitigated Sales. Sales of energy and capacity are permissible under this tariff in all balancing authority areas where the Seller has been granted market-based rate authority. Sales of energy and capacity under this tariff are also permissible at the metered boundary between the Seller's mitigated balancing authority area and a balancing authority area where the Seller has been granted market-based rate authority provided: (i) legal title of the power sold transfers at the metered boundary of the balancing authority area where the seller has market-based rate authority; and (ii) if the Seller sells at the metered boundary of a mitigated balancing authority area at market-based rates, then neither it nor its affiliates can sell into that mitigated balancing authority area from the outside. Seller must retain, for a period of five years from the date of the sale, all data and information related to the sale that demonstrates compliance with items (i) and (ii) above. 10. Seller Category. Seller is a Category 2 Seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. ?? 35.36(a), in the Northeast Region. Seller is a Category 1 Seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. ?? 35.36(a), in the Southwest, Southwest Power Pool, Southeast, Central and Northwest Regions.
